14 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
15 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
16 Article – Estates and Trusts
17 14.5–103.
18 (a) In this title the following words have the meanings indicated.
19 (v) “Revocable”, as applied to a trust, means revocable by the settlor without the
20 consent of the trustee or a person holding an adverse interest.
21 (w) (1) “Settlor” means a person, including a testator, that creates or
22 contributes property to a trust.
23 (2) “Settlor” includes a person that, with other settlors, creates or
24 contributes property to a trust in which case each such person is a settlor of the portion of
25 the trust property attributable to the contribution of that person except to the extent
26 another person has the power to revoke or withdraw that portion.
27 Article – Courts and Judicial Proceedings
28 11–504.
29 (a) (1) In this section the following words have the meanings indicated.
30 (2) “Depository institution” means a bank, credit union, trust company,
31 savings bank, or savings and loan association, or any of their affiliates or subsidiaries.
32 (3) “DISABILITY” MEANS A PHYSICAL OR MENTAL IMPAIRMENT THAT
33 RESULTS IN A SUBSTANTIAL IMPEDIMENT TO EMPLOYMENT.

SENATE BILL 939 3
1 (4) (3) “REVOCABLE TRUST” HAS THE MEANING STATED IN §
2 14.5–103 OF THE ESTATES AND TRUSTS ARTICLE.
3 (5) (4) “SETTLOR” HAS THE MEANING STATED IN § 14.5–103 OF
4 THE ESTATES AND TRUSTS ARTICLE.
5 [(3)] (6) (5) “Value” means fair market value as of the date on which the
6 execution or other judicial process becomes effective against the property of the debtor, or
7 the date of filing the petition under the federal Bankruptcy Code.
8 (f) (1) (i) In addition to the exemptions provided in subsection (b) of this
9 section, and in other statutes of this State, in any proceeding under Title 11 of the United
10 States Code, entitled “Bankruptcy”, any individual debtor domiciled in this State may
11 exempt the debtor’s aggregate interest in:
12 1. Personal property, up to $5,000; and
13 2. Subject to subparagraph (ii) of this paragraph:
14 A. Owner–occupied residential real property, including a
15 condominium unit [or], a manufactured home that has been converted to real property in
16 accordance with § 8B–201 of the Real Property Article, OR RESIDENTIAL REAL PROPERTY
17 OF A SETTLOR THAT IS HELD IN A REVOCABLE TRUST; or
18 B. A cooperative housing corporation that owns property that
19 the debtor occupies as a residence.
20 (ii) [The] SUBJECT TO SUBPARAGRAPH (III) OF THIS
21 PARAGRAPH AND PARAGRAPH (2) OF THIS SUBSECTION, THE exemption allowed under
22 subparagraph (i)2 of this paragraph may not exceed [the amount under 11 U.S.C. §
23 522(d)(1), adjusted in accordance with 11 U.S.C. § 104, subject to the provisions of
24 paragraphs (2) and (3) of this subsection] $125,000 FOR AN INDIVIDUAL.
25 (III) IF MULTIPLE INDIVIDUALS IN THE SAME BANKRUPTCY
26 PROCEEDING CLAIM THE EXEMPTION UNDER SUBPARAGRAPH (I)2 OF THIS
27 PARAGRAPH FOR THE SAME PROPERTY, THE TOTAL EXEMPTION AMOUNT MAY NOT
28 EXCEED $125,000.
29 (2) [An individual may not claim the exemption under paragraph (1)(i)2 of
30 this subsection on a particular property if:
31 (i) The individual has claimed successfully the exemption on the
32 property within 8 years prior to the filing of the bankruptcy proceeding in which the
33 exemption under this subsection is claimed; or

4 SENATE BILL 939
1 (ii) The individual’s spouse, child, child’s spouse, parent, sibling,
2 grandparent, or grandchild has claimed successfully the exemption on the property within
3 8 years prior to the filing of the bankruptcy proceeding in which the exemption under this
4 subsection is claimed.
5 (3) The exemption under paragraph (1)(i)2 of this subsection may not be
6 claimed by both a husband and wife in the same bankruptcy proceeding] FOR FISCAL YEAR
7 2028 AND EACH FISCAL YEAR THEREAFTER, THE EXEMPTION AMOUNTS SPECIFIED
8 IN PARAGRAPH (1)(II) AND (III) OF THIS SUBSECTION SHALL BE:
9 (I) ADJUSTED BY ANY CHANGE IN THE CALENDAR YEAR
10 PRECEDING THE FISCAL YEAR IN THE CONSUMER PRICE INDEX (ALL URBAN
11 CONSUMERS – UNITED STATES CITY AVERAGE – ALL ITEMS), AS PUBLISHED BY THE
12 U.S. BUREAU OF LABOR STATISTICS; AND
13 (II) ROUNDED TO THE NEAREST $25.
14 (b) (1) The following items are exempt from execution on a judgment:
15 [(1)] (I) Wearing apparel, books, tools, instruments, or appliances, in an
16 amount not to exceed $5,000 in value necessary for the practice of any trade or profession
17 except those kept for sale, lease, or barter.
18 [(2)] (II) Except as provided in subsection (i) of this section, money
19 payable in the event of sickness, accident, injury, or death of any person, including
20 compensation for loss of future earnings. This exemption includes but is not limited to
21 money payable on account of judgments, arbitrations, compromises, insurance, benefits,
22 compensation, and relief. Disability income benefits are not exempt if the judgment is for
23 necessities contracted for after the disability is incurred.
24 [(3)] (III) Professionally prescribed health aids for the debtor or any
25 dependent of the debtor.
26 [(4)] (IV) The debtor’s interest, not to exceed $1,000 in value, in household
27 furnishings, household goods, wearing apparel, appliances, books, animals kept as pets,
28 and other items that are held primarily for the personal, family, or household use of the
29 debtor or any dependent of the debtor.
30 [(5)] (V) Subject to subsection (c)(3) of this section, up to $500 in a deposit
31 account or other account of the debtor held by a depository institution, without election of
32 the debtor.
33 [(6)] (VI) Cash or property of any kind equivalent in value to $6,000 is
34 exempt, if within 30 days from the date of the attachment or the levy by the sheriff, the

SENATE BILL 939 5
1 debtor elects to exempt cash or selected items of property in an amount not to exceed a
2 cumulative value of $6,000, except that the cumulative value of cash and property
3 exempted under this item and item [(5)] (V) of this [subsection] PARAGRAPH may not
4 exceed $6,000.
5 [(7)] (VII) Money payable or paid in accordance with an agreement or court
6 order for child support.
7 [(8)] (VIII) Money payable or paid in accordance with an agreement or court
8 order for alimony to the same extent that wages are exempt from attachment under §
9 15–601.1(b)(1)(i) of the Commercial Law Article.
10 [(9)] (IX) The debtor’s beneficial interest in any trust property that is
11 immune from the claims of the debtor’s creditors under § 14.5–511 of the Estates and Trusts
12 Article.
13 [(10)] (X) With respect to claims by a separate creditor of a husband or
14 wife, trust property that is immune from the claims of the separate creditors of the husband
15 or wife under § 14.5–511 of the Estates and Trusts Article.
16 (XI) OWNER–OCCUPIED RESIDENTIAL REAL PROPERTY,
17 INCLUDING A CONDOMINIUM UNIT, A COOPERATIVE HOUSING CORPORATION THAT
18 OWNS PROPERTY THAT THE DEBTOR OCCUPIES AS A RESIDENCE, A MANUFACTURED
19 HOME, OR RESIDENTIAL REAL PROPERTY OF A SETTLOR THAT IS HELD IN A
20 REVOCABLE TRUST, IN THE FOLLOWING AMOUNTS:
21 1. EXCEPT AS PROVIDED IN ITEM 2 OF THIS ITEM,
22 $150,000 FOR AN INDIVIDUAL; AND
23 2. $300,000 FOR AN INDIVIDUAL WHO IS AT LEAST 65
24 YEARS OLD.
25 (2) (I) BEGINNING OCTOBER 1, 2027, AND EVERY 3 YEARS
26 THEREAFTER, THE EXEMPTION AMOUNTS SPECIFIED UNDER PARAGRAPH (1)(XI) OF
27 THIS SUBSECTION SHALL BE:
28 1. ADJUSTED BY ANY CHANGE IN THE CALENDAR YEAR
29 PRECEDING THE FISCAL YEAR IN THE CONSUMER PRICE INDEX (ALL URBAN
30 CONSUMERS – UNITED STATES CITY AVERAGE – ALL ITEMS), AS PUBLISHED BY THE
31 U.S. BUREAU OF LABOR STATISTICS; AND
32 2. ROUNDED TO THE NEAREST $25.
33 (II) ADJUSTMENTS MADE UNDER THIS PARAGRAPH MAY NOT
34 APPLY TO BANKRUPTCY PROCEEDINGS FILED BEFORE OCTOBER 1, 2027.

